We are a young, inclusive charity providing food, toilitries, and household goods to 30 food banks in North London.

We are looking for volunteers to pick &amp; pack in our distribution hub or deliver food to the food banks.

A fabulous opportunity to work in a place with good vibes and becoming part of the Food Bank Aid family. The hub is a great place to socialise, we have tea, coffee and cakesduring every shift and music to accompany the volunteers. You will have a fulfilling and fun experience at Food Bank Aid!

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

Established in 1966, SCCCC (Sheffield Churches Council for Community Care) is a multi award winning charity which supports older people (65+) across Sheffield, providing a &#39;helping hand&#39; when they need it most.&nbsp;We work alongside Sheffield City Council, Sheffield Teaching Hospitals and a wide range of statutory and voluntary sector partners to improve wellbeing and reduce isolation and loneliness in the city&#39;s older community.&nbsp;Staff and volunteers provide befriending support through visits and over the phone to help combat loneliness. They also provide a range of practical assistance to older people in their own homes and around admittance or discharge from hospital.&nbsp;More information about our history, ethos and services can be found at www.scccc.co.uk.&nbsp;

We currently have the following volunteer opportunities available

Community Based Roles - Friendly Visiting opportunities available all across the city, where you visit an older person in their own home

Home Based Role - Telephone Supporter opportunities both long and short term available

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

YHA Blaxhall makes a great base for exploring everything that the Suffolk coast has to offer. Comfortable and inviting, this former school is at the heart of the village, on the edge of Blaxhall Heath surrounded by wildlife and beautiful countryside.

Curl up with a book in our cosy lounge, or relax on our garden picnic benches and enjoy being surrounded by flowers!

The hostel sits on the edge of the Suffolk Coast and Heaths Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty, one of the most important areas for wildlife in the whole of Britain. For bird watching, sea food, cycling and walking, YHA Blaxhall is a great options.

Just down the road is the world famous Snape Maltings Concert Hall and you can walk around ancient burial mounds and discover the incredible&nbsp;story of the ship burial of an Anglo-Saxon King at Sutton Hoo.&nbsp; The magnificent 12th Century fortress of Framlingham Castle and the wild and remote shingle spit of Orford Ness are 8 and 6 miles away respectively.&nbsp;&nbsp;

There is on-site parking.&nbsp; &nbsp;

&nbsp;

If this is Manchester&rsquo;s coolest local library it&rsquo;s because the local teenagers who use it also designed it. The interior is filled with vibrant, bold colours, furnishings and fabrics, a perfect setting for picking up a book or using our free wifi.
We may be in a purpose built youth centre &ndash; thus the youth services and graphic novels, teen fiction, and books for young mums and dads &ndash; but this library values older people too! ESOL classes, the knitting group and the job club and IT class&nbsp;are for all to enjoy.

Love books? Love people? Then find out how you can volunteer with The Reader.

The Reader is based in Liverpool and works across England and Wales to set up Shared Reading groups.

Shared Reading is a great way for people to meet up and read and listen to brilliant stories and poems. Then we talk about them. There&#39;s never any pressure&nbsp;to read aloud or talk. Listening is fine too. And we can talk about them in any way we want to. They might spark a memory or there might be a character we like, or a word or phrase that stands out.&nbsp;

We already suppport Shared Reading in Warrington Hospital and LifeTime Gateway and we&#39;re looking to expand our work in Warrington so we are looking for new volunteers to help start groups as Reader Leaders. New groups might be in community centres, cafes, a bookshop or other places. We find the locations and set it all up - although suggestions for new venues are always welcome. Perhaps you know somewhere.&nbsp;

All our groups are led by Reader Leaders. A Reader Leader gets full training and ongoing support from our excellent team.&nbsp;

To volunteer with us, you have to enjoy reading a wide variety of material. You have to&nbsp; be available 4 hours per week or fortnight to prepare and deliver a session. Training is&nbsp;on Zoom, for 6 half day sessions over 6 weeks. Groups are held in weekday daytimes - so this is when you have to be available.&nbsp;

Sport Volunteering provides a wide range of opportunities for students and staff to volunteer in and around the local community. If you are looking for&nbsp;an opportunity to develop your skills, gain experience within sport and physical activity or&nbsp;to give back whilst having fun,&nbsp;we provide accessible sporting opportunities in multiple sports for&nbsp;all ages and abilities.&nbsp;

Current popular junior opportunities volleyball, squash and tennis and childrens holiday sports camps.&nbsp;We also run a varied programme of&nbsp;sport and wellbeing opportunites for adults from hard to reach communities aimed at improving physical and mental health.&nbsp;

Students can also access our Community Sport Activator programme as part of their volunteering and receive mentoring and assistance in accessing formal qualifications, informal CPD as well as receiving a University recognised volunteering award.&nbsp;

&nbsp;

The Westmorland and Furness Cohesion Group&#39;s mission is to create safe, connected communities characterised by resilience, mutual respect, understanding and a sense of identity and belonging for everyone in Westmorland &amp; Furness.

Our group is formed of a wide range of members from across Westmorland and Furness including charities, voluntary organisations, sports groups, public organisations and business who work together to achieve our mission.&nbsp;

To achieve our mission we will run and support a number of activities, and need enthusiastic volunteers to help.

We are a local branch of&nbsp;An Comunn G&agrave;idhealach which is a company limited by guarantee and a voluntary membership organisation, with charitable status, founded in Oban in 1891 as a vehicle for the preservation and development of the Gaelic language.&nbsp;

It actively encourages the teaching, learning and use of the Gaelic language and the study and cultivation of Gaelic literature, history, music and art.&nbsp;An Comunn Gaidhealach founded&nbsp;&nbsp;a Gaelic Festival modelled on the Welsh Eisteddfod&nbsp;in 1892. This Festival was called&nbsp;The M&ograve;d&nbsp;and it is a result of considerable&nbsp;endeavors that now, over 100 years later due recognition has been granted to the Mod in the form of the Royal&nbsp;assent. The Festival is now&nbsp;The Royal National M&ograve;d.&nbsp;

The Charity No. is SCO01282.&nbsp;

The Association is usually referred to as &ldquo;An Comunn&rdquo;, the Association. For many throughout the world An Comunn is the body which represents the Gaelic language.

As a local branch we create opportunities to celebrate and promote Gaelic language and culture such as the Oban &amp; District Provincial Mod which is a smaller version of the National Festival. A lot of our volunteers do not speak Gaelic and there is no requirement to speak the language in order to support and promote it.&nbsp;

OBJECTIVES OF AN COMUNN G&Agrave;IDHEALACH

The aims of the Association are to support and develop all aspects of the Gaelic language, culture, history and heritage at local, national and international levels by:


	Promoting the use of the language in everyday community life.
	Promoting the study and development of Gaelic language, literature, music, drama and all other related art forms.
	Actively seeking official recognition and use of Gaelic as a living language and national asset by local, national and European Governments and other agencies, by co-operating with all other organisations engaged in the provision of Gaelic language and culture
	An Comunn G&agrave;idhealach is non-political and non-sectarian, and membership is open to anyone sharing the above objectives

This hostel is a rare Grade I listed Elizabethan manor house set in stunning National Trust countryside in the heart of Shropshire.&nbsp; With its Great Hall and spiral staircases it is a historic masterpiece and a quirky place to stay.&nbsp; It underwent a &pound;500,000 refurbishment in 2012 to bring it bang up to date. Perfect for people who enjoy walking as there is lovely countryside nearby and the waymarked trails of the Cardingmill Valley and the Long Mynd are just 7 miles away.&nbsp; Convenient for both the Ironbridge Gorge and its museums and the castle town of Ludlow.&nbsp;&nbsp;

The building is open to National Trust visitors between 2pm and 5pm on Wednesdays and Sundays.&nbsp; There are no locks on any of the bedroom doors&nbsp;owing to the age of the house.&nbsp;

Volunteering with YHA is a fantastic way to have fun, learn new skills, boost your CV and travel to different places. We have a variety of different opportunities to choose from and volunteering roles to suit everyone. &nbsp;

The tasks are varied and in return you will meet some great people, who both work and stay in our hostels, as well as enjoying your time off discovering the local area and attractions.

Tees Valley Arts is a charity that supports people to live creative lives. They have been working at the intersection of community and the arts for over 40 years. They are the only organisation committed to working across all five boroughs of the Tees Valley and across all art forms. Over the last 6 years they have developed a reputation for excellence in co-curating with communities leading to their recognition as an NPO in the most recent round of Arts Council funding. In recent years they have delivered co-curated programmes on behalf of TVCA, Middlesbrough Council, National Lottery Heritage Fund and Historic England. They are currently delivering the Redcar Palace project, establishing a new arts centre on the Redcar seafront on behalf of Redcar Council.&nbsp;

&nbsp;

Redcar Palace is a home to;


	An ongoing exciting exhibition programme featuring artists from our region and around the world
	Honestly Made Honestly Sold, our honesty shop featuring handmade and locally sourced goods from over 50 different local sellers
	Blooming Youth Collective &ndash; our peer led youth group for 16 to 24 year olds focused on wellbeing, inclusivity and friendship
	Which Craft? Ladies, a free to attend drop-in craft group for women every Wednesdays
	Life drawing with Simon Edwards on Thursdays from 6pm to 8pm
	A community space to talk, learn and teach


We offer volunteer placements in a relaxed surroundings,&nbsp;


	Within the gallery and outside the gallery&nbsp;
	Front of house
	Working in a exhibition&nbsp;&nbsp;
	Media
	Printing
	Certain aspects of the business side&nbsp;


&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

The St John&rsquo;s Project (SJP) is a Registered Charity set up to provide support for St John the Baptist&rsquo;s church in Chester. This is the oldest building in the city still in use for its original purpose.&nbsp;It has a long and rich history intimately interwoven with that of Chester itself.

The SJP support takes two forms: managing a small cafe and shop and providing a guide service for visitors to the church. We need volunteers to help with both of these activities in a number of ways. The Church is open to visitors from 10 a.m. until 4p.m. Monday to Saturday (11 to 3 in winter). Sunday is for worship only.

Cafe and Shop

The cafe offers hot and cold drinks and packaged snacks at very reasonable prices from a purpose-built area within the church; while the shop provides a range of souvenirs and other articles.&nbsp; There are also hundreds of second-hand books and magazines for sale.

Guide Service

There has been a church on this site since for almost 1400 years and the present church dates from 1075. So, there is an enormous fund of stories to tell.&nbsp; These have been condensed into a structured guided tour which is offered free to visitors.

Volunteering Opportunities

We need enthusiastic people who can:


	Assist with the Cafe and Retail area;
	Be part of the Visitor experience in our Tour Service*;
	Help with administration duties;
	Develop and maintain our social media offerings;
	Assist&nbsp; with fund-raising; and
	Get involved in new schemes and projects.


&nbsp;

*Full training will be provided

For an Application Form email:&nbsp;office@stjohnschester.uk

&nbsp;

Enjoy panoramic views of the lake and mountains from one of the most spectacularly situated YHA&#39;s in England. Overlooking England&rsquo;s largest natural lake, YHA Windermere offers the chance to stay in an idyllic countryside setting only 2 miles from Windermere and its many attractions and 4 miles from Ambleside.&nbsp;&nbsp;

An ideal base for anyone wanting to escape the crowds.&nbsp; The hostel has large wooded grounds with trails and wildlife to enjoy.&nbsp; &nbsp;Relax with a drink on the terrace and enjoy good quality food from the hostel&#39;s newly refurbished restaurant and bar.&nbsp;

Around 100m from the hostel is a self-contained camping facility block and up to 20 campers can pitch there year round.&nbsp; Seasonally, bell tents and tipis are available.&nbsp;&nbsp;

Volunteering with YHA is a fantastic way to have fun, learn new skills, boost your CV and travel to different places. We have a variety of different opportunities to choose from and volunteering roles to suit everyone. &nbsp;

The tasks are varied and in return you will meet some great people, who both work and stay in our hostels, as well as enjoying your time off discovering the local area and attractions.

YHA Castleton Losehill Hall is a totally refurbished Victorian gothic mansion and cobbled mews set in formal gardens and 27 acres of parkland in the heart of the Peak District National Park.

There are beautiful gardens, woods and streams to explore within the grounds with one of the peak&rsquo;s most popular and charming tourist villages on the doorstep.&nbsp;

Castleton is a quaint village with a lot of history.&nbsp; Why not visit Peak Cavern, Peveril Castle, or walk the hills around Mam Tor to find an Iron Age hill fort.&nbsp; If you want to explore the industrial past of Castleton why not go to Treak Cliff Cavern or the Speedwell Mine and the Blue John mine still produces its distinctive purplish-yellow stone.&nbsp;&nbsp;

Further afield are the towns of Buxton and Bakewell - experience the echo in the centre of the dome of the former Devonshire Hospital at Buxton, now part of Derby University -&nbsp;or try the culinary delight of authentic Bakewell pudding.&nbsp;&nbsp;

Volunteering with YHA is a fantastic way to have fun, learn new skills, boost your CV and travel to different places. We have a variety of different opportunities to choose from and volunteering roles to suit everyone. &nbsp;

The tasks are varied and in return you will meet some great people, who both work and stay in our hostels, as well as enjoying your time off discovering the local area and attractions.

&nbsp;

Grimm &amp; Co is a registered charity and our core purpose is to change lives one story at a time. We support under-resourced children and young people aged 0 to 18 with their confidence and skills around creativity and writing.

We introduce children, young people and families to discover creativity and imagination through artists, one-to-one mentoring and exciting projects which spark motivation to write. We know that strong writing skills and an ability to imagine beyond what we experience are fundamental to future success. We also believe it is important for young people to see a real reason to write so there is always an outcome from the activities we do.&nbsp;&nbsp;

We are a story destination for all ages in our &lsquo;Apothecary to the Magical&rsquo;. As you enter you are immediately transported into a world of wonder and enchantment. Warm greetings from friendly shopkeepers take you on a tour of wild schemes, mysterious plots and kitchenware.&nbsp; We encourage you to visit the UK&rsquo;s one and only&nbsp;&lsquo;Apothecary to the Magical&rsquo;&nbsp;visible to humans in Yorkshire.

Little do you know there&rsquo;s a secret door, hidden within the shelves, that takes you on a further journey of awe and wonder, starting with the imagination gym for dusting off old apathy and unleashing hidden creativity. Once the imagination is sparked one can climb the giant&rsquo;s bookcase through the corridor of glory, past Graham and Grizelda&rsquo;s office, glimpsing at the Writers&rsquo; Closet, through to the Writers&rsquo; Pad.

Grimm &amp; Co is built on a foundation of research that defined the way we work. Our model of working is also inspired by the 826 Valencia model and we are a member of the Ministry of Stories family &ndash; sharing practices, keeping our offer fresh, exciting, on mission and relevant. Dave Eggers also tells the story about 826&rsquo;s inspiration, early beginnings, and ensuing momentum in a&nbsp;TED Talks&nbsp;video.

Grimm &amp; Co is a literacy charity that relies on an amazing team of volunteers.&nbsp; &nbsp;If you have a little free time on your hands (even just one morning or afternoon each month) and you&rsquo;d like to get involved with what we do, we&rsquo;d love to welcome you on board. No matter where your skills and interests lie, we&rsquo;ll have a role that suits you!&nbsp; Have a read of the volunteer roles on our website and see what you think.&nbsp;&nbsp;Volunteering - Grimm &amp; Co - Come and join our team (grimmandco.co.uk)



&nbsp;

&nbsp;

Hello, and welcome to The Glowsticks Project!

Our charity exists to support children, young people and adults with Autism and ADHD (and co-existing conditions). We have many different provisions that we run, such as 5 and under stay and play, crafts, forest school, art therapy and much more.&nbsp;

We run a Cafe that is open to the public 5 days a week with a hugely diverse workforce with a combination of volunteers and paid staff: 80% of our people have Autism and/or ADHD, including the founder, Rebecca, who also has Autism.&nbsp;

On site, we have a sensory room, games consoles, a pool table and lots more for our young people and children!

Our cafe is a cololurful, welcoming happy place and have been recently awarded Dementia Friendly accreditation too because of the environment we have created.&nbsp;

We serve a lovely variety of meals and hot drinks - come and see us!&nbsp;

Age UK Cheshire is a local organisation working with older people, their families, and their carers to support them in living their best lives. We do this by helping people to combat poverty, relieve social isolation and increase their independence. We want to create a future where every older person in Cheshire has the opportunity to live their best life.

We are an independent, local registered charity but work with others, including national&nbsp;Age UK, and other local Age UKs who are all also independent charities.

&nbsp;

Thank you for your interest in volunteering with Surrey&rsquo;s Tree Planting and Establishment Team. With your support we can work together to plant 1.2 million trees across Surrey to ease the effects of climate change and benefit biodiversity. We are hugely grateful that you have shown an interest in helping us.&nbsp;&nbsp;

Volunteers are at the heart of what we do and are essential to the running and continued success of our tree planting and establishment programme.&nbsp;

We are a small, friendly team delivering our tree planting objectives who are looking forward to seeing you this winter to help us plant trees!&nbsp;

What to expect from your day


	We offer morning and/or afternoon sessions, and sometimes for our larger sites you can stay all day if you wish.
	There are scheduled tea and lunch breaks&nbsp;&nbsp;
	It is essential that all volunteers wear suitable outdoor, comfortable clothing (layers are good and old clothing that you do not mind getting dirty in) and decent footwear such as walking boots or Wellingtons (no sandals, high heels or flip flops please - it has happened before!)&nbsp;&nbsp;
	Waterproof clothing is essential if it is a bit rainy and sunscreen/hats etc should be brought along for sunnier days&nbsp;&nbsp;
	Please bring a packed lunch to enjoy a picnic alfresco together (under cover if it unfortunately rains), a foldable chair if you have one and a bottle of water too. ?&nbsp;
	You will get all the details that you need for your volunteering session closer to the day.&nbsp; This includes directions, public transport links, parking, toilet facilites if there are any - or the nearest loos!


Why Spend the day with us

By tree planting with us you will get the opportunity to work outdoors in Surrey&rsquo;s beautiful countryside, and join an existing friendly volunteer tree planting team, offering a wide variety of benefits, including:&nbsp;


	Fun, sociable and a great opportunity for healthy exercise&nbsp;
	Great for mind, body and spirit as volunteering in the countryside has proven widespread health &amp; wellbeing benefits&nbsp;
	A great sense of personal achievement and self-worth&nbsp;
	An opportunity to develop new skills and meet like-minded people&nbsp;
	Improve your employability by giving you valuable experience&nbsp;
	A safe, professionally led volunteering experience, as all our tasks are run by trained staff or Tree Wardens and are fully insured&nbsp;&nbsp;


Corporate Volunteering

We also offer sessions for corporate groups.&nbsp; Please email trees@surreycc.gov.uk if you are interested in bringing your work team to volunteer.&nbsp; We can send you details of our rates for businesses.

How to get in Touch

You can email us at trees@surreycc.gov.uk

Pedal for Scotland returns for our 19th year on 10th September 2017. Pedal for Scotland&rsquo;s main event day will feature the 45 mile Classic Challenge from Glasgow to Edinburgh and the colossal 93 mile Big Belter from Glasgow to Edinburgh using the first 20 miles of the Classic Challenge route. Stay tuned as we announce our Wee Jaunt rides over the coming months!

&nbsp;

For more information about the event visit our website;&nbsp;http://pedalforscotland.org&nbsp;

We are a Dorset based charity providing supported holidays for local people living with a disability.&nbsp;Every summer we create a touch of holiday magic by bringing together small groups of holidaymakers with teams of dedicated volunteers for a week of friendship and fun.

Our holidays are based at Wraxall Yard, situated in the peaceful hamlet of Lower Wraxall, near Dorchester. Surrounded by beautiful countryside, Wraxall Yard is a beautifully transformed set of previously derelict barns, adapted to the highest of standards to provide accessible accommodation for people living with disabilities.&nbsp;The site is at the centre of an organic family farm and also features a livestock barn and workshop for visitors to get involved in farming and wildlife activities.

https://greenislandholidaytrust.com

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

Campus is an entirely volunteer-run charity committed to providing annual respite breaks for disadvantaged children, having run summer projects every year since 1967. We work with some of the most vulnerable children in the Liverpool-Merseyside area: children in care, some who have been abused, young carers, and children living in poverty or overcrowded accommodation. These children are referred to us by parents, social workers and other organisations because they desperately need a break from their home lives. For some, it is the one chance they get each year to be a child.

When asked why Campus is so special, a word that constantly comes up is community. Lots of Campus kids return to the same project each year from the age of 6, providing them with much needed stability in their positive relationships with the adult volunteers. When they reach 13, many stay on to become Young Helpers themselves, and are trained to volunteer on the projects that they benefited from.

More information on our projects and volunteer roles can be found on our website:&nbsp;https://campusholidays.org.uk&nbsp;
